), physician, younger brother of Robert Southey. to the London University, to &c &c. It is reported he was heard to say the day before he died: “One is gratified to give so many people pleasure by one’s death!” Which is a[s]Letter omitted.
       curious a saying (impossible in any epoch but this) as I have heard for some time. His £10,000 to the Browngs struck me as probably less than they expected, but yet as the right sum.He had also supplemented their income by £100 a year since the birth of their son in 1849. Poor Kenyon, he was a very well-disposed, fat easy-going man; trying always to do rather good among his fellow creatures, if he did anything.

It was half an hour too late for dressing for the Goderichs, and I was quite fluttered and knocked awry, when Kingsley, at that late hour, came in upon me; stamm[er]edLetters omitted. Charles Kingsley had a pronounced stammer in conversation, which disappeared in public speaking. babbled, and did nothing but smoke a little tobacco,—till I absolutely broke off, and went most of the way in a Cab. It was all very well; the Goderichs good with a small dull party (Bruces, Doyle, fat-boy’s Brother-in-lawHenry Austin Bruce (1815–95; ODNB) and Norah, b. Napier (1827?1827?–97; 
